I was wonder if the accepted age of the universe is trust-worthy. I decided to take it upon myself to explore the validity of the value. The universe we live in isn't static and it keeps expanding. Because of this expanding nature, light from other galaxies observe from Earth appear to be redshifted the further away they are from us. The universe contains billions of galaxies, each galaxies contains miliions of stars. By calculating their distant away from us, I can then find out the constant rate that causes the expanding of the universe. Once I know this constant, I can essentially turn back time to the point of the Big Bang to determine the age of the universe. I started by collecting valuable data/information. I order to caculate the age of the universe, I was able to collect data for approximately 4320 galaxies:
